feat: natural-language filter per run (optional user_instructions)

New optional field on POST /api/process/{batch_id}:

    { "user_instructions": "Exclude beverages and desserts." }

When provided, the directive is appended to the user message on every
per-page Opus call — never to the system prompt, so prompt caching
stays intact and the filter is scoped to a single run. Blank /
whitespace-only input is treated as absent. Input is capped at 2000
characters server-side (Pydantic) to keep tokens bounded.

End-to-end path:
  Upload.tsx   textarea + 3 example chips + char counter
  client.ts    apiStartProcessing(batchId, userInstructions?)
  processing.py StartProcessingBody(user_instructions: str | None)
  pipeline.py  run_pipeline(..., user_instructions=)
                _run_extraction(..., user_instructions=)
  extraction.py extract_from_bytes(..., user_instructions=)
                _call_one_chunk(..., user_instructions=)
                Appends a SECOND text block after the generic directive
                when instructions are present. The block is guarded:
                Opus is told to ignore anything that would break the
                schema or invent dishes, and to never emit prose
                outside the JSON object.

Upload.tsx also gains an honest "Typical extraction · 15–45 s per menu
page" caption next to the submit button so the user sees an expected
runtime, not a mystery spinner.

Landing grid picks up a new row:
  Natural-language filter per run    Only Mise

Tests:
  test_extraction_user_instructions.py
    - None and whitespace-only inputs add NO second text block
    - Real text produces exactly TWO text blocks (directive + user)
    - User text never leaks into the system prompt (cache prefix)
  test_processing.py
    - Accepts valid body (202)
    - Rejects oversize body > 2000 chars (422)
    - Empty body stays backward compatible (202)

Full suite: 74 passed. Frontend build clean.
